  "prompt": "Are you actually supposed to break people's ribs when performing CPR?",
  "response": "When performing CPR, breaking ribs can happen, and it's often seen as a side effect of the necessary force applied during chest compressions. The primary goal of CPR is to circulate blood to the brain and other vital organs when someone's heart has stopped, and effective chest compressions are critical for this.\n\nThe American Heart Association advises that chest compressions should be done with sufficient force (at least 2 inches deep at a rate of 100 to 120 compressions per minute) to be effective. While breaking ribs can occasionally occur, it is generally considered an acceptable risk when performing CPR, especially on adults. The priority is to provide life-saving care.\n\nIf you are trained in CPR, focus on delivering high-quality compressions. If you or someone else is concerned about rib fractures, it's important to remember that the immediate goal is to save lives, and rib fractures can be treated after the person has been stabilized. Always seek to receive proper training or refreshers in CPR from certified organizations to ensure you're performing it correctly.",
